    <section class="container section-pad pillar">
      <h2>Complete Guide to Electrical Code Corrections in West Michigan</h2>
      <p>
        Code corrections are the catch-all category for "this wiring isn't dangerous today but it doesn't meet current
        code" — and Michigan, like every state on the 2020 NEC, has a long list of these conditions. They're usually
        triggered by one of three events: a home sale where the buyer's inspector flags issues, a remodel that opens
        walls and modifies circuits, or an insurance carrier requiring remediation as a condition of writing or
        renewing a policy.
      </p>
      <p>
        This guide covers the most common code-correction scopes we run across Holland, Grand Rapids, and the broader
        West Michigan region.
      </p>

      <h3>The Big Categories</h3>
      <ul>
        <li>
          <strong>Aluminum branch wiring (1965–1973 era).</strong> Aluminum at receptacles and switches loosens and
          overheats. Remediation options range from COPALUM crimps to full receptacle replacement. See
          <a href="/blog/aluminum-wiring-what-to-do">aluminum wiring: what to do if you have it</a>.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Knob-and-tube wiring (pre-1940).</strong> Not inherently unsafe in original installs, but insulation
          contact, amateur splices, and overloading make it a real risk. Many insurers refuse coverage on active K&amp;T.
          See <a href="/blog/knob-and-tube-wiring-what-to-do">knob-and-tube wiring: what to do if you still have it</a>.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Federal Pacific Stab-Lok and Zinsco panels.</strong> Documented failure-to-trip in independent
          testing. Replace regardless of size or condition. See
          <a href="/blog/zinsco-fpe-panel-replacement">Zinsco and Federal Pacific panels: why they need to go</a>.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Missing AFCI protection (<a href="/glossary/nec-210-12">NEC 210.12</a>).</strong> Required in most
          living spaces. Older homes are grandfathered, but renovations trigger code-compliance requirements.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Missing or non-functional <a href="/glossary/gfci">GFCI</a> protection.</strong> Required in
          bathrooms, kitchens, garages, outdoors, and within 6 feet of any sink. Often missing in older homes.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Bonding and grounding deficiencies.</strong> Improperly bonded sub-panels, missing ground rods,
          corroded grounding electrode connections. See <a href="/glossary/bonding-vs-grounding">bonding vs
          grounding</a>.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Backstabbed receptacles and switches.</strong> Cheap spring-clip terminations loosen and arc over
          time. Re-terminate to side screws or replace with spec-grade devices.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Service entrance issues.</strong> Undersized conductors, corroded meter bases, missing main bonding
          jumper at the service. See <a href="/glossary/service-entrance">service entrance</a>.
        </li>
      </ul>

      <h3>Insurance-Triggered Corrections</h3>
      <p>
        Increasingly common across West Michigan: a routine homeowner's policy inspection flags one of the categories
        above, the carrier sends a 30-90 day remediation notice, and the homeowner has a tight window to address it.
        We do this work on a documented basis — invoice, permit, inspection result — exactly what the carrier needs
        to close the file.
      </p>
      <p>
        The most common insurance triggers in our service area:
      </p>
      <ul>
        <li>Federal Pacific or Zinsco panel found during inspection.</li>
        <li>Active knob-and-tube in occupied living spaces.</li>
        <li>Aluminum branch wiring with no documented mitigation.</li>
        <li>Visible amateur splices in attic or basement.</li>
        <li>Service entrance corrosion or improper grounding.</li>
      </ul>

      <h3>Renovation-Triggered Corrections</h3>
      <p>
        When a remodel opens walls or modifies circuits, the affected circuits typically must meet current code. The
        common ones:
      </p>
      <ul>
        <li>Adding AFCI breakers to the bedrooms, living rooms, and kitchens being remodeled.</li>
        <li>Bringing receptacle spacing up to NEC 210.52 (one receptacle within 6 ft of any wall space, all kitchen
          counter spaces served).</li>
        <li>Adding GFCI protection to any wet location.</li>
        <li>Tamper-resistant receptacles in dwelling units (NEC 406.12).</li>
      </ul>
      <p>
        We coordinate this scope with general contractors and other trades when we're part of a larger remodel,
        keeping the permit and inspection on the original project rather than a separate code-correction permit.
      </p>

      <h3>Home-Sale Inspection Findings</h3>
      <p>
        Buyer's home inspectors flag a predictable list of issues in West Michigan homes. Most of them are real and
        worth addressing; some are recommended best practices rather than code violations. We provide a written
        assessment that separates the two, with quotes for each item so you (or the seller) can negotiate
        appropriately.
      </p>

      <h3>What "Bringing It Up to Code" Costs</h3>
      <p>
        Code-correction projects vary widely. A simple aluminum receptacle remediation might run $400–$800. A whole-house
        knob-and-tube replacement can run $8,000–$25,000+. A Federal Pacific panel replacement with 100 → 200 amp upgrade
        runs $2,800–$5,500. We quote each line item explicitly so you see exactly what each correction costs and which
        ones are mandatory vs recommended.
      </p>

      <h3>West Michigan Specifics</h3>
      <p>
        Michigan adopted the 2020 NEC with state amendments. Most West Michigan AHJs (Holland, Hudsonville, Grand
        Rapids, Allegan County) follow standard NEC interpretations; lakeshore townships occasionally have local
        amendments around outdoor lighting (dark-sky) and lake-adjacent service entrance protection. We know which
        AHJ wants what and which inspectors look for what.
      </p>
